<section xml:id="sec-7-5" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Applications of Exponential Functions</title>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Overview</title>
<p>In this Lesson we consider doubling time and half-life. Try to get students to understand this fundamental difference between linear and exponential functions: while linear functions increase or decrease by equal amounts over equal time intervals, exponential functions increase or decrease by equal factors over equal time intervals. If possible, it is also desirable for students to understand that there is nothing special about the factor 2; it is merely convenient.</p>
    
<p>At this point in their study of exponential functions, students begin to confuse the various parameters. Take a few minutes to review some basic definitions: <m>P(t)</m>  is a variable, but <m>P_0</m> is a constant; <m>r</m> is the percent growth rate and <m>b=1+r</m> is the growth factor; and so on.</p></commentary>

<activity><title>Doubling-Time</title>  

<task><p>Lately the inflation rate in Freedonia has been 8% annually. ("Inflation" means that prices are rising by 8% per year.) Write a formula for the price <m>P</m> of a $5 item as a function of time, <m>t</m>.</p></task>  

<task><p>How long will it take for the price to double from $5 to $10? (Round to the nearest year.)</p></task>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Round the the doubling time to 9 years to simplify the sketch in part (d).</p></commentary>

